# apache-kafka Best Practices

Apache Kafka is a powerful distributed streaming platform. To leverage its full potential, follow these best practices for code organization, performance, and testing.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use a Clear Package Structure
Organize your Kafka-related code into distinct packages for producers, consumers, and configuration. This improves maintainability and readability.

```plaintext
src/main/java/com/example/kafka/
├── config/
│   └── KafkaConfig.java
├── producer/
│   └── UserEventProducer.java
└── consumer/
    └── UserEventConsumer.java
```

### Centralize Configuration
Keep all Kafka configurations in a single class. This promotes reuse and makes it easier to manage changes.

```java
public class KafkaConfig {
    public static Properties producerProps() {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put("bootstrap.servers", "localhost:9092");
        props.put("acks", "all");
        props.put("compression.type", "lz4");
        props.put("key.serializer", "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer");
        props.put("value.serializer", "org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer");
        return props;
    }
}
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use Idempotent Producers
Always configure your producers to be idempotent to prevent duplicate messages.

```java
props.put("enable.idempotence", "true");
```

❌ BAD: Not using idempotent producers can lead to duplicate messages.
✅ GOOD: Always enable idempotence to ensure exactly-once delivery.

### Implement Manual Offset Management
Set `enable.auto.commit=false` and manage offsets manually to avoid data loss.

```java
consumer.commitSync();
```

❌ BAD: Relying on automatic commits can lead to lost messages.
✅ GOOD: Manually commit offsets after processing messages.

## Performance Considerations

### Optimize Producer Throughput
Use `acks=all` and `min.insync.replicas=2` to ensure data safety without sacrificing throughput.

```java
props.put("acks", "all");
props.put("min.insync.replicas", "2");
```

❌ BAD: Using default settings can compromise data integrity.
✅ GOOD: Configure producers with `acks=all` and `min.insync.replicas=2` for safety.

### Use LZ4 Compression
Enable LZ4 compression for better throughput without significant latency.

```java
props.put("compression.type", "lz4");
```

❌ BAD: Using no compression can lead to increased bandwidth usage.
✅ GOOD: Use LZ4 for optimal performance.

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Unnecessary Rebalances
Enable static membership by setting `group.instance.id` to prevent unnecessary rebalances.

```java
props.put("group.instance.id", "my-consumer-instance");
```

❌ BAD: Not using static membership can lead to frequent rebalances.
✅ GOOD: Use static membership to stabilize consumer groups.

### Monitor Consumer Lag
Implement monitoring for consumer lag as a primary operational metric to ensure consumers are keeping up with the producers.

```java
// Pseudocode for monitoring consumer lag
long lag = getLag(consumerGroupId);
if (lag > threshold) {
    alertAdmin();
}
```

❌ BAD: Ignoring consumer lag can lead to data processing delays.
✅ GOOD: Regularly monitor and alert on consumer lag.

## Testing Approaches

### Use Embedded Kafka for Testing
Utilize Embedded Kafka for unit tests to simulate Kafka interactions without needing a real Kafka cluster.

```java
@ClassRule
public static final EmbeddedKafkaRule embeddedKafka = new EmbeddedKafkaRule(1, true, "test-topic");

@Test
public void testProducer() {
    // Your test code here
}
```

❌ BAD: Testing against a real Kafka cluster can be slow and error-prone.
✅ GOOD: Use Embedded Kafka for fast, reliable tests.

### Validate Schema Compatibility
Always validate message schemas using Schema Registry to ensure backward and forward compatibility.

```java
// Example of schema validation
SchemaRegistryClient schemaRegistryClient = new CachedSchemaRegistryClient("http://localhost:8081", 100);
Schema schema = schemaRegistryClient.getLatestSchema("my-topic-value");
```

❌ BAD: Not validating schemas can lead to runtime errors.
✅ GOOD: Always validate schemas against the Schema Registry.

By following these best practices, you will ensure that your Apache Kafka implementation is efficient, maintainable, and robust. Make these guidelines a part of your daily development workflow to optimize your Kafka applications.